      "system": {
        "description": "<div class=\"boxgroup flexrow boxrow\">\n<div class=\"flexcol box\" style=\"justify-content: flex-start;\">\n<h4 class=\"nogrow\" style=\"margin: 0.5em;\">Features</h4>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 217\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>Large, green-skinned ogre</p>\n<p>Turtle shell on its back</p>\n<p>Iron cage on its shell</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"flexcol box\" style=\"justify-content: flex-start;\">\n<h4 class=\"nogrow\" style=\"margin: 0.5em;\">Drives</h4>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 217\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>Capture weaker creatures for meat and study</p>\n<p>Eat the tender meat of young ones</p>\n<p>Gorge on Eintykara honey</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"flexcol box\" style=\"justify-content: flex-start;\">\n<h4 class=\"nogrow\" style=\"margin: 0.5em;\">Tactics</h4>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 217\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>Defend with its invulnerable shell</p>\n<p>Trap victims in its cage</p>\n<p>Squeeze and crush with their size</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 218\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 43\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 46\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 51\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>The Ookempan are large ogres who generally lead a simple life with strict traditions. When they come of age, they craft their first &ldquo;life cage&rdquo; which is then attached to the shells on their back. As they age, their shells grow around parts of the cage thereby anchoring it there for the rest of their life.</p>\n<p>Life cages serve the two major pursuits in Ookempan culture. The first is food. Any other non-Ookempan species, no matter if they are sentient or not, is viewed as potential food. There are elaborate cooking traditions in Ookempan society, and the young of other species are particularly sought after for their tender meat.</p>\n<p>The second major pursuit of these turtle-like people is that of knowledge and study. Any subject caught and placed in their life cage who is not eaten will be left there for study. They may see how long a subject can live without food or water, how they react to various plants or concoctions, and even perform elaborate autopsies. In this way, the Ookempans hope to master the power of life itself.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Quest Starter:</p>\n<p>For days, a Junglelander could be heard calling out hoarsely for help. A group followed the sound back to an Ookempan camp where several people were marked as a part of an upcoming feast. It seems the camp is now being decorated for a festival, so the meal must be soon. Can the people be saved without incurring the Ookempan&rsquo;s wrath?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"section\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<blockquote>\n<p><em>Your Truth:</em></p>\n<p><em>Do the Ookempan have elaborate books of knowledge, or do they pass on what they learn through detailed stories with complex morals?</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>",
